00:00:26.240 --> 00:00:30.470
PROFESSOR: Let's get started.

00:00:30.470 --> 00:00:37.670
We want to wrap up today
our discussion of atoms

00:00:37.670 --> 00:00:40.970
without external
field, and then discuss

00:00:40.970 --> 00:00:46.850
what happens when we put atoms
into external magnetic fields.

00:00:46.850 --> 00:00:51.400
Last class, we talked
about isotope shifts,

00:00:51.400 --> 00:00:55.472
and there was a question, how
big are those isotopes for some

00:00:55.472 --> 00:00:56.430
of your favorite atoms?

00:00:59.640 --> 00:01:02.150
I just looked up
some information

00:01:02.150 --> 00:01:06.330
on lithium, which
is a light atom,

00:01:06.330 --> 00:01:10.590
and this paper here
shows calculations

00:01:10.590 --> 00:01:13.175
compared with experiments.

00:01:13.175 --> 00:01:16.050
The isotope shift between
lithium six and lithium seven

00:01:16.050 --> 00:01:18.760
due to the mass, lithium
six to lithium seven,

00:01:18.760 --> 00:01:20.940
is about 10 gigahertz.

00:01:20.940 --> 00:01:25.360
The volume effect is only two
megahertz, 1,000 times smaller.

00:01:25.360 --> 00:01:27.170
However, the precision
of experiments

00:01:27.170 --> 00:01:30.170
is such that if you
find an isotope shift,

00:01:30.170 --> 00:01:32.972
the mass effect can
be exactly calculated

00:01:32.972 --> 00:01:36.350
from the atomic masses, you
can still get information

00:01:36.350 --> 00:01:39.610
about the size of the
atomic nucleus out of it.

00:01:39.610 --> 00:01:44.360
So this is the example of a
light atom, 10 gigahertz mass

00:01:44.360 --> 00:01:46.360
effect, two megahertz
volume effect.

00:01:52.240 --> 00:01:55.340
And here is a rubidium atom.

00:01:55.340 --> 00:02:00.080
The isotope shift of the
D1 line between 85 and 87

00:02:00.080 --> 00:02:03.920
is 77 megahertz only.

00:02:03.920 --> 00:02:08.609
The mass shift is 56
megahertz, and the remainder

00:02:08.609 --> 00:02:11.700
is mainly the volume effect.

00:02:11.700 --> 00:02:14.770
There's a specific mass effect
due to electronic correlations

00:02:14.770 --> 00:02:17.800
if you calculate electrons,
which I think is small here

00:02:17.800 --> 00:02:19.960
but I don't want to discuss it.

00:02:19.960 --> 00:02:25.170
We can now compare
the mass effect

00:02:25.170 --> 00:02:28.300
in rubidium versus lithium.

00:02:28.300 --> 00:02:33.265
First of all, the shift
compared to infinite mass.

00:02:33.265 --> 00:02:37.020
the reduced mass effect,
is much bigger in lithium.

00:02:37.020 --> 00:02:41.180
It's 20 times bigger in
lithium than in rubidium.

00:02:41.180 --> 00:02:44.400
However, when you go from
lithium six to lithium seven,

00:02:44.400 --> 00:02:48.850
the mass changes by 15%,
so the delta m over m

00:02:48.850 --> 00:02:51.620
is also much larger for
lithium than rubidium.

00:02:51.620 --> 00:02:53.725
And if you add
those two factors,

00:02:53.725 --> 00:02:57.285
you find that the mass
effect is 200 times larger

00:02:57.285 --> 00:03:03.440
in lithium, 10 gigahertz
versus 50 megahertz.

00:03:03.440 --> 00:03:05.960
The nuclear volume
effect is two megahertz

00:03:05.960 --> 00:03:08.830
for lithium, 20
megahertz for rubidium,

00:03:08.830 --> 00:03:12.660
so that sets the scale.

00:03:12.660 --> 00:03:14.680
Any questions about that?

00:03:20.010 --> 00:03:27.970
Let me come back to one
other question which

00:03:27.970 --> 00:03:37.130
we discussed last
class, and this

00:03:37.130 --> 00:03:41.375
was the question
about if you have

00:03:41.375 --> 00:03:45.300
a deformation of a
nucleus, or if you have

00:03:45.300 --> 00:03:50.360
any kind of isotropic
shape of an object,

00:03:50.360 --> 00:03:52.906
what is the minimum
angular momentum in order

00:03:52.906 --> 00:03:54.440
to observe it?

00:03:54.440 --> 00:03:57.220
I know a lot of you
got confused about it,

00:03:57.220 --> 00:04:01.890
so I want to discuss
the same thing again,

00:04:01.890 --> 00:04:06.772
but now focusing on two
different frames, the lab frame

00:04:06.772 --> 00:04:09.310
and the body-fixed frame.

00:04:09.310 --> 00:04:11.410
I hope you find this
discussion insightful.

00:04:37.510 --> 00:04:42.828
So let's assume we have an
object, it can be a molecule.

00:04:42.828 --> 00:04:45.018
Actually, you have a
homework assignment

00:04:45.018 --> 00:04:47.770
whether you can observe
a permanent dipole

00:04:47.770 --> 00:04:50.100
moment of a molecule,
and this will lead you

00:04:50.100 --> 00:04:55.440
into a discussion of lab
frame versus body-fixed frame.

00:04:55.440 --> 00:04:57.850
But let's assume
we have an object,

00:04:57.850 --> 00:05:01.970
assume it's a nucleus, which
has a really odd shape.

00:05:01.970 --> 00:05:07.600
However, if it has
angular momentum of zero,

00:05:07.600 --> 00:05:12.950
all you have is one level.

00:05:12.950 --> 00:05:20.760
If you have an angular momentum
of 1/2, you have two levels,

00:05:20.760 --> 00:05:24.530
and you can now define
in the laboratory

00:05:24.530 --> 00:05:27.830
that the energy difference
is due to the magnetic dipole

00:05:27.830 --> 00:05:30.601
moment, for instance, or
the electric dipole moment

00:05:30.601 --> 00:05:34.497
if you put in electric field.

00:05:34.497 --> 00:05:43.877
If you have I equals
1, you can have

00:05:43.877 --> 00:05:52.215
three levels, E1, E0, E minus 1.

00:05:54.850 --> 00:05:58.240
Let's say you have put the
atoms into an electric field

00:05:58.240 --> 00:05:59.520
gradient.

00:05:59.520 --> 00:06:09.430
You can then ask if E0 is in
the middle between up and down,

00:06:09.430 --> 00:06:13.270
plus 1 or minus 1, or whether
it's displaced or not.

00:06:13.270 --> 00:06:18.510
And depending whether this is
larger or smaller than zero,

00:06:18.510 --> 00:06:21.790
you would say there is a
quadrupole moment which

00:06:21.790 --> 00:06:24.400
is larger or smaller than zero.

00:06:24.400 --> 00:06:28.220
In other words, what I'm telling
you is if you have only one

00:06:28.220 --> 00:06:32.940
level, I equals 0,
you can't say anything

00:06:32.940 --> 00:06:34.485
about the shape of the object.

00:06:34.485 --> 00:06:38.090
If you have two levels, you
can determine a dipole moment.

00:06:38.090 --> 00:06:40.690
If you have three
levels, by the deviation

00:06:40.690 --> 00:06:45.340
from the equidistance, you can
find a higher order moment.

00:06:50.230 --> 00:06:54.035
But now comes the point.

00:06:54.035 --> 00:06:55.670
You can now take two positions.

00:06:58.300 --> 00:07:09.680
You can say that for low I,
the deformation of a magnetic

00:07:09.680 --> 00:07:13.920
moment for I equals
0 cannot be measured.

00:07:27.810 --> 00:07:30.230
Therefore, it is zero.

00:07:30.230 --> 00:07:46.880
Or you can say deformation
exists, but only not in the lab

00:07:46.880 --> 00:07:51.104
frame but in the
body-fixed frame.

00:07:54.010 --> 00:07:58.410
So in other words, you would
say that the deformation exists

00:07:58.410 --> 00:07:59.090
always.

00:07:59.090 --> 00:08:01.640
It's just a measurement problem.

00:08:01.640 --> 00:08:04.370
At low angular momentum,
I cannot measure.

00:08:04.370 --> 00:08:08.970
Or the other statement would be,
well, if you can't measure it,

00:08:08.970 --> 00:08:12.210
[INAUDIBLE], it means
it doesn't exist.

00:08:12.210 --> 00:08:16.847
So which statement or which
conclusion is correct?

00:08:34.070 --> 00:08:36.901
This is the body-fixed
frame argument,

00:08:36.901 --> 00:08:39.391
and this is more based
on the lab frame.

00:08:43.380 --> 00:08:49.090
Well, I would say the lab frame
argument is always correct

00:08:49.090 --> 00:08:50.996
because you can't
measure it, you

00:08:50.996 --> 00:08:54.730
can't determine it in the
lab, but let me go from there.

00:08:54.730 --> 00:09:00.430
Let's assume we have
an object, and we

00:09:00.430 --> 00:09:03.614
think it has a deformation but
it has a low angular momentum

00:09:03.614 --> 00:09:05.920
phase.

00:09:05.920 --> 00:09:10.395
Can we still say that
in its body-fixed frame,

00:09:10.395 --> 00:09:15.630
we have an object which
has a deformation or not?

00:09:15.630 --> 00:09:21.300
Now, my personal opinion
is the following.

00:09:21.300 --> 00:09:22.794
It really depends.

00:09:22.794 --> 00:09:26.430
If you have a system
where you can have

00:09:26.430 --> 00:09:30.000
angular momentum
without changing

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:31.530
the internal structure.

00:09:31.530 --> 00:09:34.865
For instance, I have this stick,
and I can just spin it up,

00:09:34.865 --> 00:09:37.740
and if I can spin it up, I can
get an angular momentum wave

00:09:37.740 --> 00:09:41.840
packet, I can orient it and
measure its deformation.

00:09:41.840 --> 00:09:47.060
Then I think I would say, even
if this state has zero angular

00:09:47.060 --> 00:09:50.230
momentum, it has a
deformation, and the way

00:09:50.230 --> 00:09:53.110
I know it because if I
add angular momentum,

00:09:53.110 --> 00:09:54.940
I can measure the deformation.

00:09:54.940 --> 00:09:57.570
I cannot measure it at
low angular momentum.

00:09:57.570 --> 00:09:59.970
So then you would say in
the body-fixed system,

00:09:59.970 --> 00:10:03.480
there is a deformation, but
it only manifests itself

00:10:03.480 --> 00:10:07.980
in the lab frame if I
add angular momentum.

00:10:07.980 --> 00:10:12.450
However, you may have an
object, let's say a molecule,

00:10:12.450 --> 00:10:16.880
which is so weakly bound
that one quantum of angular

00:10:16.880 --> 00:10:21.490
momentum due to centrifugal
forces rips it apart.

00:10:21.490 --> 00:10:22.670
That exists.

00:10:22.670 --> 00:10:27.560
Extremely bound state which
cannot provide enough binding

00:10:27.560 --> 00:10:32.130
force to withstand even one
unit of angular momentum.

00:10:32.130 --> 00:10:35.000
So that's an object
which you cannot rotate,

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:38.695
you cannot transfer any angular
momentum without destroying it,

00:10:38.695 --> 00:10:41.130
without ripping it apart.

00:10:41.130 --> 00:10:45.850
And now to say that this
molecule has a dipole moment

00:10:45.850 --> 00:10:51.010
or has some anisotropy, you're
making a statement which cannot

00:10:51.010 --> 00:10:52.210
be tested at all.

00:10:52.210 --> 00:10:54.374
So at that point, you
should rather say,

00:10:54.374 --> 00:10:56.290
what matters is what I
can measure in the lab,

00:10:56.290 --> 00:10:57.748
and I will never
be able to measure

00:10:57.748 --> 00:11:01.140
any deformation in the lab.

00:11:01.140 --> 00:11:06.560
So the first example
with the stick

00:11:06.560 --> 00:11:09.170
will apply to a very
stable molecule which

00:11:09.170 --> 00:11:11.844
may have a dipole
moment, and you

00:11:11.844 --> 00:11:13.885
assume it has the same
dipole moment whether it's

00:11:13.885 --> 00:11:15.450
rotating or not.

00:11:15.450 --> 00:11:18.160
And then you would say
at zero angular momentum,

00:11:18.160 --> 00:11:21.910
I cannot measure the dipole
moment but I know it exists

00:11:21.910 --> 00:11:22.910
in the body-fixed frame.

00:11:25.640 --> 00:11:30.330
If you have a
nucleus, and you have

00:11:30.330 --> 00:11:33.930
sort of a wave function of
the protons and neutrons,

00:11:33.930 --> 00:11:38.640
and it's I equals 0, you
will not find any moment.

00:11:38.640 --> 00:11:40.690
At least for the
ground state of nuclei,

00:11:40.690 --> 00:11:42.880
when you add angular
momentum, you really

00:11:42.880 --> 00:11:44.720
change the internal structure.

00:11:44.720 --> 00:11:47.706
You have to promote
nucleons to higher orbits,

00:11:47.706 --> 00:11:50.715
so you cannot add angular
momentum and still have

00:11:50.715 --> 00:11:51.410
the same object.

00:11:51.410 --> 00:11:53.835
So therefore, you have
to say the ground state

00:11:53.835 --> 00:11:56.595
with I equals 0 has no
deformation, because there

00:11:56.595 --> 00:11:59.541
is no way to ever find
[INAUDIBLE] deformation,

00:11:59.541 --> 00:12:02.010
so it doesn't exist.

00:12:02.010 --> 00:12:04.370
But there are excited
states of nuclei

00:12:04.370 --> 00:12:08.370
which have a deformation,
and these deformed nuclei

00:12:08.370 --> 00:12:12.110
can be put into a multiplex
of angular momentum states.

00:12:12.110 --> 00:12:16.270
So then you would see, I have
the same kind of nucleus,

00:12:16.270 --> 00:12:19.490
but at different
angular momentum states.

00:12:19.490 --> 00:12:21.910
At higher angular
momentum states,

00:12:21.910 --> 00:12:24.814
you can define [INAUDIBLE]
determine quadrupole moments

00:12:24.814 --> 00:12:26.950
and things like this.

00:12:26.950 --> 00:12:30.730
And then you may say the
same internal state has now

00:12:30.730 --> 00:12:33.990
a non-rotating state, and
you would still be tempted,

00:12:33.990 --> 00:12:37.770
and you are correct with that,
to associate a deformation even

00:12:37.770 --> 00:12:39.010
in the non-rotating state.

00:12:42.380 --> 00:12:45.850
I hope those remarks help
you reconcile the two aspects

00:12:45.850 --> 00:12:50.020
whether you have an object which
is stable enough to be spun up,

00:12:50.020 --> 00:12:51.530
and then I think
you can always talk

00:12:51.530 --> 00:12:53.175
about the body-fixed frame.

00:12:53.175 --> 00:12:56.240
But if you have an object
where you change the internal

00:12:56.240 --> 00:12:59.930
structure when you add
angular momentum, I think,

00:12:59.930 --> 00:13:03.072
for fundamental reasons,
you cannot associate any

00:13:03.072 --> 00:13:06.270
deformation with it.

00:13:06.270 --> 00:13:07.746
Any questions about that?

00:13:16.720 --> 00:13:20.920
Let me just write
down the summary.

00:13:20.920 --> 00:13:36.270
The definition of a deformation
in a body-fixed frame

00:13:36.270 --> 00:13:55.850
makes sense only if you can
add or change angular momentum

00:13:55.850 --> 00:14:05.756
without significantly changing
the internal structure.

00:14:29.176 --> 00:14:29.675
Questions?

00:14:58.440 --> 00:15:00.310
I think the computer is set up.

00:15:00.310 --> 00:15:02.584
I cannot go backward
in Presentation mode.

00:15:17.385 --> 00:15:22.860
What I want to discuss
next is give you

00:15:22.860 --> 00:15:26.315
a little bit of an historic
summary how spectroscopy

00:15:26.315 --> 00:15:30.960
of hydrogen is developed,
in particular also focusing

00:15:30.960 --> 00:15:34.335
on one important discovery,
the discovery of QED

00:15:34.335 --> 00:15:37.100
through the Lamb shift.

00:15:37.100 --> 00:15:42.340
Of course, you all love hydrogen
because it's the simplest atom

00:15:42.340 --> 00:15:45.580
but it has so much
interesting physics in it.

00:15:45.580 --> 00:15:49.160
I've summarized for you here
some papers on hydrogen,

00:15:49.160 --> 00:15:53.030
and I used them to
illustrate several points.

00:15:53.030 --> 00:15:57.040
I will show you that actually,
the discovery of the Lamb shift

00:15:57.040 --> 00:15:58.580
had precursors.

00:15:58.580 --> 00:16:01.700
10 years before the Lamb
shift was discovered,

00:16:01.700 --> 00:16:03.740
people had even some
idea that something

00:16:03.740 --> 00:16:05.910
may be wrong with
the understanding

00:16:05.910 --> 00:16:07.360
of the structure of hydrogen.

00:16:07.360 --> 00:16:10.690
So you can say they came
so close, people 10 years

00:16:10.690 --> 00:16:14.367
before, in realizing
the Lamb shift,

00:16:14.367 --> 00:16:16.200
there were people who
maybe missed the Nobel

00:16:16.200 --> 00:16:18.560
prize by just a tiny little bit.

00:16:18.560 --> 00:16:20.510
They had all the
insight that there

00:16:20.510 --> 00:16:22.801
may be QED correction
in hydrogen.

00:16:22.801 --> 00:16:24.300
They just didn't
have the technology

00:16:24.300 --> 00:16:27.150
to measure it accurately enough.

00:16:27.150 --> 00:16:29.120
The second example
I want to show

00:16:29.120 --> 00:16:32.980
is that we always talk about
fundamental limitations,

00:16:32.980 --> 00:16:35.450
but fundamental limitations
can disappear in time

00:16:35.450 --> 00:16:39.710
because they may not be as
fundamental as they appear.

00:16:39.710 --> 00:16:51.266
So for instance,
there were limitations

00:16:51.266 --> 00:16:52.970
with the limitations
of the Lamb shift

00:16:52.970 --> 00:16:55.720
because you had a short
lifetime of p states,

00:16:55.720 --> 00:16:58.330
but with the event of
two photon transition,

00:16:58.330 --> 00:17:02.380
you can go from s to
s and s to d states,

00:17:02.380 --> 00:17:04.450
and therefore map
out Lamb shifts

00:17:04.450 --> 00:17:06.980
with much, much higher
precision not limited

00:17:06.980 --> 00:17:12.060
by the finite
lifetime of p states.

00:17:12.060 --> 00:17:16.640
Finally, you would say Lamb
shifts are small splittings,

00:17:16.640 --> 00:17:19.152
and for many, many
years, Lamb shifts

00:17:19.152 --> 00:17:21.855
were measured by
making radio frequency

00:17:21.855 --> 00:17:24.665
transitions between
two s and two p states.

00:17:24.665 --> 00:17:28.590
Well, today, the most accurate
measurement of the Lamb shift

00:17:28.590 --> 00:17:30.156
is with an optical
transition where

00:17:30.156 --> 00:17:32.290
you need a much, much
higher relative precision

00:17:32.290 --> 00:17:34.760
to see the tiny Lamb shift.

00:17:34.760 --> 00:17:39.666
But optical metrology with
direct frequency measurements

00:17:39.666 --> 00:17:43.380
and frequency combs has so
much improved in precision

00:17:43.380 --> 00:17:46.126
that now, an optical
measurement, even if it comes

00:17:46.126 --> 00:17:49.070
to a tiny difference, is
more accurate than a direct

00:17:49.070 --> 00:17:50.350
[INAUDIBLE].

00:17:50.350 --> 00:17:52.310
So I think the
history of hydrogen

00:17:52.310 --> 00:17:55.067
shows you that
technology can completely

00:17:55.067 --> 00:17:57.990
change the paradigm how
measurements are made.

00:17:57.990 --> 00:18:00.280
Fundamental limits
disappear because new tools

00:18:00.280 --> 00:18:02.720
or new insight is available.

00:18:02.720 --> 00:18:06.360
And also, I find it interesting
that discoveries often

00:18:06.360 --> 00:18:10.925
have precursors, and people
have a hunch, know about it,

00:18:10.925 --> 00:18:13.297
and then finally,
it is discovered.

00:18:13.297 --> 00:18:15.380
Let me just take you through
some historic papers.

00:18:32.640 --> 00:18:39.160
This paper is 1933, 15
years before the Lamb shift,

00:18:39.160 --> 00:18:42.170
and it says that one
possible explanation

00:18:42.170 --> 00:18:45.250
for some discrepancy of the
structure of the Balmer lines

00:18:45.250 --> 00:18:48.060
is that the effect
of the interaction

00:18:48.060 --> 00:18:50.680
between the radiation field and
the atom has been neglected.

00:18:50.680 --> 00:18:52.015
That's QED.

00:18:52.015 --> 00:18:55.758
You cannot just calculate the
structure of the hydrogen atom

00:18:55.758 --> 00:18:57.150
from the Coulomb field.

00:18:57.150 --> 00:19:00.660
You have to allow the
radiation field, all the modes

00:19:00.660 --> 00:19:02.400
of the vacuum to be included.

00:19:02.400 --> 00:19:04.830
So this insight
is not due to Lamb

00:19:04.830 --> 00:19:10.450
It was there already, 1933.

00:19:10.450 --> 00:19:14.910
Same year, look at the
title, "On the Breakdown

00:19:14.910 --> 00:19:18.500
of the Coulomb Law for
the Hydrogen Atom."

00:19:18.500 --> 00:19:24.360
People speculated or discussed
that the Coulomb law will not

00:19:24.360 --> 00:19:27.090
be valid at very
small distances.

00:19:27.090 --> 00:19:30.640
This is ultimately what QED,
raided correction, the Lamb

00:19:30.640 --> 00:19:33.480
shift, vacuum
polarization all is about.

00:19:39.950 --> 00:19:42.740
Finally, people had an
understanding of the hydrogen

00:19:42.740 --> 00:19:45.060
atom, and they
measure-- I want you

00:19:45.060 --> 00:19:47.900
to keep that in mind--
they did optical.

00:19:47.900 --> 00:19:55.350
They measured the Balmer lines
of hydrogen and deuterium,

00:19:55.350 --> 00:19:59.270
and they couldn't
fully resolve it

00:19:59.270 --> 00:20:02.400
because of the finite
lifetime of the peak state,

00:20:02.400 --> 00:20:05.180
but there was some
hunch when you

00:20:05.180 --> 00:20:10.030
try to get the envelope from
the underlying structure

00:20:10.030 --> 00:20:11.780
that there was a discrepancy.

00:20:11.780 --> 00:20:14.600
It was just not significant
enough to say for sure,

00:20:14.600 --> 00:20:16.370
there is an
additional line shift

00:20:16.370 --> 00:20:18.758
which is not accounted
for by theory.

00:20:27.670 --> 00:20:29.129
There was a
discussion that there

00:20:29.129 --> 00:20:32.560
is a deviation of the Coulomb
law, but here is the insight.

00:20:32.560 --> 00:20:35.390
As was indicated by
previous authors,

00:20:35.390 --> 00:20:38.465
the interaction required
to change the Coulomb law

00:20:38.465 --> 00:20:41.340
at small distances
is much too large

00:20:41.340 --> 00:20:43.410
to be accounted for
by the assumption

00:20:43.410 --> 00:20:46.180
of a finite size of
electron and proton.

00:20:46.180 --> 00:20:48.155
So the Coulomb field
has to be modified

00:20:48.155 --> 00:20:53.485
at short distances in a
much stronger way than just

00:20:53.485 --> 00:20:55.710
the finite size of the proton.

00:20:55.710 --> 00:20:58.690
We'll talk about the finite
size of the proton in a minute.

00:20:58.690 --> 00:21:04.180
And then, of course,
1947, UIF oscillators

00:21:04.180 --> 00:21:07.360
have been developed in
the pursuit of radar,

00:21:07.360 --> 00:21:11.060
experimental tools are there
now-- high power IF sources,

00:21:11.060 --> 00:21:13.680
cumulative sources,
and such, and then

00:21:13.680 --> 00:21:15.834
Lamb and Retherford
in his landmark paper

00:21:15.834 --> 00:21:20.025
look at the fine structure
of the hydrogen atom,

00:21:20.025 --> 00:21:22.310
and this is the famous result.

00:21:22.310 --> 00:21:28.510
They measured transitions as
a function of magnetic field,

00:21:28.510 --> 00:21:30.860
and you see the solid
line, which I think

00:21:30.860 --> 00:21:33.430
was the theory without
the Lamb shift.

00:21:33.430 --> 00:21:38.460
The dashed line is the hyper
fine structure of hydrogen,

00:21:38.460 --> 00:21:41.630
and the lines converge,
and the difference

00:21:41.630 --> 00:21:46.214
is 1,000 megacycles, the first
determination of the Lamb

00:21:46.214 --> 00:21:48.150
shift.

00:21:48.150 --> 00:21:50.950
So this was 1947.

00:21:50.950 --> 00:21:55.450
It's interesting
that it's just one

00:21:55.450 --> 00:21:58.450
or two weeks later, there is
a theoretical paper by Hans

00:21:58.450 --> 00:22:03.000
Bethe providing an explanation
for the Lamb shift,

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:06.510
so already coming up
with the first model

00:22:06.510 --> 00:22:10.770
how to account for QED.

00:22:10.770 --> 00:22:12.910
I didn't look it
up in detail, but I

00:22:12.910 --> 00:22:15.450
thought the spirit was similar
to what I presented you

00:22:15.450 --> 00:22:17.335
in class, that the
electromagnetic zero point

00:22:17.335 --> 00:22:23.210
energy is shaping the electron
and leading to corrections.

00:22:23.210 --> 00:22:26.840
But it's amazing that
within weeks, theorists

00:22:26.840 --> 00:22:29.770
figured nearly out, yes,
this is the explanation.

00:22:29.770 --> 00:22:32.120
This is how we have
to explain the theory.

00:22:36.300 --> 00:22:40.930
For a number of years,
people pursued measurements

00:22:40.930 --> 00:22:44.250
of the Lamb shifts with
higher and higher accuracy.

00:22:44.250 --> 00:22:47.390
I just like the
last sentence here.

00:22:47.390 --> 00:22:52.330
This is now the next paper by
Willis Lamb and Retherford,

00:22:52.330 --> 00:22:55.150
and they are sort of saying that
they wanted to measure the Lamb

00:22:55.150 --> 00:22:56.900
shift with higher
precision, but then they

00:22:56.900 --> 00:22:59.630
said, "the program was
large and encountered

00:22:59.630 --> 00:23:03.260
unexpected difficulties
which required much more time

00:23:03.260 --> 00:23:04.290
to surmount.

00:23:04.290 --> 00:23:08.070
As a result, the paper promised
two years ago was delayed."

00:23:08.070 --> 00:23:10.930
I think this applies to many,
many papers to be written,

00:23:10.930 --> 00:23:14.300
but here, the authors
even say that upfront,

00:23:14.300 --> 00:23:16.905
it took us two years
longer to do the research

00:23:16.905 --> 00:23:18.234
than we initially anticipated.

00:23:20.990 --> 00:23:23.990
You see now the
growing accuracy.

00:23:23.990 --> 00:23:26.770
We have the Lamb shift, which
is on the order of 1,000

00:23:26.770 --> 00:23:29.255
megacycles, one gigahertz,
and the precision

00:23:29.255 --> 00:23:31.900
is now in the 100
kilohertz range.

00:23:31.900 --> 00:23:36.731
This was the technology
of the original discovery.

00:23:36.731 --> 00:23:40.995
Then there was a next
generation of experiments

00:23:40.995 --> 00:23:45.490
on the Lamb shift using
separated [? oscilloatomic ?]

00:23:45.490 --> 00:23:49.260
fields, [INAUDIBLE] techniques.

00:23:49.260 --> 00:23:51.340
We'll talk about that
later in the course.

00:23:51.340 --> 00:23:54.840
And with these techniques,
the accuracy of the Lamb shift

00:23:54.840 --> 00:24:03.378
is now one digit further
in the 10 kilohertz region.

00:24:06.560 --> 00:24:10.590
There is a nice feature that
we'll also discuss later,

00:24:10.590 --> 00:24:14.400
that it was possible to
obtain line weights, which

00:24:14.400 --> 00:24:15.930
is [INAUDIBLE].

00:24:15.930 --> 00:24:18.260
We'll talk about
it later, but it's

00:24:18.260 --> 00:24:25.010
possible to do spectroscopy on
unstable states, which provides

00:24:25.010 --> 00:24:29.083
line widths narrower than
the actual line widths.

00:24:29.083 --> 00:24:32.200
If you want to get one
sentence as an appetizer,

00:24:32.200 --> 00:24:35.970
you just look at the
atoms which have not

00:24:35.970 --> 00:24:38.930
decayed for a long time,
and if you play some tricks,

00:24:38.930 --> 00:24:43.210
you can then get line
widths which covers points

00:24:43.210 --> 00:24:46.970
to several lifetimes, and not
just to the one [INAUDIBLE]

00:24:46.970 --> 00:24:48.380
lifetime.

00:24:48.380 --> 00:24:50.520
Some conditions have to
be met, and those authors

00:24:50.520 --> 00:24:54.220
used it here to
advantage to narrow

00:24:54.220 --> 00:24:56.360
the line for the measurement
of the Lamb shift.

00:24:56.360 --> 00:24:56.860
Yes?

00:24:56.860 --> 00:24:59.180
AUDIENCE: The abstract
says that the result is not

00:24:59.180 --> 00:25:00.530
in good agreement with theory.

00:25:00.530 --> 00:25:06.040
What is the theoretical--
how far had it gone?

00:25:06.040 --> 00:25:08.870
PROFESSOR: I don't
know it at this point.

00:25:08.870 --> 00:25:10.900
I will later give you
comparison with theory

00:25:10.900 --> 00:25:14.090
which is highly accurate.

00:25:14.090 --> 00:25:18.811
I assume at this
point-- I'm not sure

00:25:18.811 --> 00:25:20.540
if it was instrumental
difficulty.

00:25:20.540 --> 00:25:21.528
I didn't [INAUDIBLE].

00:25:29.790 --> 00:25:33.340
So these are the same authors
just a few years later.

00:25:33.340 --> 00:25:35.320
The agreement between
theory and experiment

00:25:35.320 --> 00:25:37.986
is two standard deviations, so I
think this problem disappeared.

00:25:37.986 --> 00:25:42.810
I don't know if it was the
fault of theory or experiment.

00:25:42.810 --> 00:25:47.680
But now we go a step forward
to optical spectroscopy.

00:25:47.680 --> 00:25:51.480
You remember originally, and
this is why the Lamb shift was

00:25:51.480 --> 00:25:56.960
not jumping into people's eye
when they did spectroscopy

00:25:56.960 --> 00:25:59.810
of the Balmer
spectrum of hydrogen,

00:25:59.810 --> 00:26:02.680
you cannot resolve
the structure.

00:26:02.680 --> 00:26:05.540
The Lamb shift is
there, but it's

00:26:05.540 --> 00:26:09.650
hidden in the envelope
of the unresolved lines.

00:26:09.650 --> 00:26:14.550
And now the advent
of lasers, and people

00:26:14.550 --> 00:26:17.952
immediately developed
saturation spectroscopy.

00:26:17.952 --> 00:26:19.410
That's how most of
our laboratories

00:26:19.410 --> 00:26:22.010
stabilize lasers using
Doppler-free saturation

00:26:22.010 --> 00:26:23.220
spectroscopy.

00:26:23.220 --> 00:26:25.460
And when saturation
spectroscopy was invented

00:26:25.460 --> 00:26:28.950
by Hansch and Schawlow
for the first time,

00:26:28.950 --> 00:26:31.230
you can break through
the Doppler [INAUDIBLE],

00:26:31.230 --> 00:26:33.510
and now you see
the lines resolved.

00:26:33.510 --> 00:26:36.120
And here, I think
for the first time,

00:26:36.120 --> 00:26:39.065
you see two peaks
separated and the splitting

00:26:39.065 --> 00:26:43.140
is the Lamb shift, which
until then was only accessible

00:26:43.140 --> 00:26:46.370
through [INAUDIBLE]
frequency methods.

00:26:46.370 --> 00:26:50.496
Of course, these were the first
lasers, just pulsed lasers,

00:26:50.496 --> 00:26:52.880
and we couldn't even
think about precision.

00:26:55.640 --> 00:26:58.400
But then, of course,
using metrology,

00:26:58.400 --> 00:27:04.750
using frequency chains, people
could do precision measurements

00:27:04.750 --> 00:27:09.100
in the optical domain.

00:27:09.100 --> 00:27:11.930
These are now papers in the
'90s, "Optical Measurement

00:27:11.930 --> 00:27:20.110
on the Lamb Shift in the Ground
State or in the Excited State."

00:27:20.110 --> 00:27:23.380
Talking about the comparison
with experiment and theory,

00:27:23.380 --> 00:27:26.670
experimental is pushed to
higher and higher precision,

00:27:26.670 --> 00:27:29.800
and suddenly, there
was a discrepancy,

00:27:29.800 --> 00:27:33.300
and it was a discrepancy
in the 1s Lamb shift.

00:27:33.300 --> 00:27:35.344
In the 1s state, the
Lamb shift is much bigger

00:27:35.344 --> 00:27:41.630
than in the 2s state because
the electron interacts much more

00:27:41.630 --> 00:27:46.225
intimately with the [INAUDIBLE]
than the Coulomb potential is

00:27:46.225 --> 00:27:47.600
on this.

00:27:47.600 --> 00:27:50.270
People found that the
experiment did no longer

00:27:50.270 --> 00:27:52.490
agree with theory.

00:27:52.490 --> 00:27:56.630
But then the theorists had to
check all their assumptions,

00:27:56.630 --> 00:28:00.565
and it was found that there
were two new binding corrections

00:28:00.565 --> 00:28:02.505
which were surprisingly large.

00:28:02.505 --> 00:28:06.030
Often, you make an estimate
that those terms are small.

00:28:06.030 --> 00:28:08.917
You say it's higher
order, but you may not

00:28:08.917 --> 00:28:10.200
know the pre-factor.

00:28:10.200 --> 00:28:12.350
And here, something
was surprisingly large,

00:28:12.350 --> 00:28:14.440
and by now you're
proving the theory.

00:28:14.440 --> 00:28:18.520
There was again agreement
between experiment and theory.

00:28:18.520 --> 00:28:21.780
It's getting now down
to the kilohertz level.

00:28:21.780 --> 00:28:28.610
And at least as a few years
ago, this was state of the art.

00:28:28.610 --> 00:28:32.090
Remember the Lamb shift is about
1,000 cycles one gigahertz,

00:28:32.090 --> 00:28:34.988
and now the precision is
in the single kilohertz.

00:28:39.930 --> 00:28:42.620
As I pointed out,
precision was reached

00:28:42.620 --> 00:28:46.860
by directly measuring the
frequency of laser, frequency

00:28:46.860 --> 00:28:48.850
metrology.

00:28:48.850 --> 00:28:52.950
This was actually, for historic
interest, frequency metrology,

00:28:52.950 --> 00:29:00.320
they used peak nodes
between the laser used

00:29:00.320 --> 00:29:04.380
to measure the hydrogen
line and some other lasers.

00:29:04.380 --> 00:29:08.620
This is just a few years
before comb generators.

00:29:08.620 --> 00:29:10.926
Frequency combs completely
changed things again.

00:29:10.926 --> 00:29:13.594
But they had already the
precision of a direct frequency

00:29:13.594 --> 00:29:15.330
measurement.

00:29:15.330 --> 00:29:18.090
You can read about
it when I paused it.

00:29:18.090 --> 00:29:19.510
It shows you what
the [INAUDIBLE]

00:29:19.510 --> 00:29:22.810
is in those installations.

00:29:22.810 --> 00:29:25.150
This is a slide I
borrowed from Ted Hansch,

00:29:25.150 --> 00:29:27.545
"Optical Spectroscopy
of Hydrogen."

00:29:27.545 --> 00:29:32.440
It just shows the advances
in frequency metrology.

00:29:36.530 --> 00:29:41.060
It shows how caesium clocks
and optical spectroscopy,

00:29:41.060 --> 00:29:43.960
how they have
changed in precision,

00:29:43.960 --> 00:29:47.485
and eventually, we
are now past the time

00:29:47.485 --> 00:29:52.470
where optical spectroscopy is
more accurate than microwave

00:29:52.470 --> 00:29:54.895
and radio frequency
spectroscopy.

00:29:54.895 --> 00:29:58.290
Optical clocks are more accurate
than [INAUDIBLE] frequency

00:29:58.290 --> 00:29:59.760
standards.

00:29:59.760 --> 00:30:02.400
I'm sure in your
lifetime, you will

00:30:02.400 --> 00:30:04.620
experience the
redefinition of this

00:30:04.620 --> 00:30:08.870
again because the caesium clock
is no longer accurate enough

00:30:08.870 --> 00:30:11.870
compared with the most
precise optical measurements.

00:30:14.870 --> 00:30:18.090
And I think there was a peak
gap, a change in slope here.

00:30:18.090 --> 00:30:23.156
In the old days, you measured
the wavelengths of light

00:30:23.156 --> 00:30:27.870
by making a measurement of
the wavelengths using maybe

00:30:27.870 --> 00:30:30.860
a grading or interferometry,
but when you now

00:30:30.860 --> 00:30:33.560
started to measure
frequencies directly,

00:30:33.560 --> 00:30:36.990
then there was a change in
slope and major improvements

00:30:36.990 --> 00:30:38.376
in precision.

00:30:38.376 --> 00:30:40.686
And today, of course, the
most precise measurement

00:30:40.686 --> 00:30:45.180
of laser frequencies is not
through the wavelengths,

00:30:45.180 --> 00:30:49.284
that they can count the number
of cycles in a peak node

00:30:49.284 --> 00:30:51.679
with an optical comb generator.

00:30:54.560 --> 00:30:57.244
So what can you do with
ever increasing precision?

00:31:00.450 --> 00:31:03.880
This is also a slide I
borrowed from Ted Hansch.

00:31:03.880 --> 00:31:08.960
If you measure very, very
accurately an atomic line,

00:31:08.960 --> 00:31:13.555
let's say the 1s 2s transition
in hydrogen using two photon

00:31:13.555 --> 00:31:17.258
spectroscopy, what you can
do is you can measure it,

00:31:17.258 --> 00:31:19.960
and a few years later,
you can measure it again.

00:31:19.960 --> 00:31:22.165
And now it becomes an
interesting question

00:31:22.165 --> 00:31:23.290
if you have this precision.

00:31:23.290 --> 00:31:26.734
Will the result be the
same as a function of time?

00:31:26.734 --> 00:31:33.550
If there were a small change,
which there wasn't, you

00:31:33.550 --> 00:31:35.040
could only come
to one conclusion,

00:31:35.040 --> 00:31:38.460
and this is fundamental
common sense in nature,

00:31:38.460 --> 00:31:40.710
change is a function of time.

00:31:40.710 --> 00:31:43.190
So this precision
of metrology is now

00:31:43.190 --> 00:31:46.828
being used to test the
fundamental constants, again,

00:31:46.828 --> 00:31:49.238
constant as a function of time.

00:31:57.790 --> 00:32:00.380
Precision is even
more improving.

00:32:00.380 --> 00:32:04.575
The latest in the development
in the spectroscopy of hydrogen

00:32:04.575 --> 00:32:09.026
is what is called the
size of the proton atom.

00:32:09.026 --> 00:32:11.805
In your homework
assignment, you are actually

00:32:11.805 --> 00:32:16.300
calculating what is the
correction due to transition

00:32:16.300 --> 00:32:19.330
frequencies in
hydrogen because you

00:32:19.330 --> 00:32:22.438
don't have a proton field
of a point particle.

00:32:22.438 --> 00:32:24.310
The proton has a finite size.

00:32:24.310 --> 00:32:27.520
Or vice versa, if you have
sufficient prediction,

00:32:27.520 --> 00:32:31.020
if you have sufficient
accuracy of the measurement,

00:32:31.020 --> 00:32:33.632
you can determine the
size of the proton

00:32:33.632 --> 00:32:35.340
from the measured
transition frequencies.

00:32:37.950 --> 00:32:44.160
This was done, and in 2010,
there was a big surprise

00:32:44.160 --> 00:32:48.415
that the size of the proton
determined from hydrogen

00:32:48.415 --> 00:32:52.290
spectroscopy did not agree
with scattering measurements

00:32:52.290 --> 00:32:56.592
where you scatter electrons and
protons to measure the proton

00:32:56.592 --> 00:32:58.330
size.

00:32:58.330 --> 00:33:00.970
This is still a puzzle.

00:33:00.970 --> 00:33:02.835
It's called the
proton radius puzzle,

00:33:02.835 --> 00:33:07.705
and it is not clear
what is causing it.

00:33:07.705 --> 00:33:11.952
What happened is in 2010,
there was a big improvement

00:33:11.952 --> 00:33:15.110
in measuring the
size of the proton,

00:33:15.110 --> 00:33:20.440
and this was done by replacing
the electron with a muon, which

00:33:20.440 --> 00:33:25.425
is a heavy electron, but since
the muon is so much heavier,

00:33:25.425 --> 00:33:29.470
the bore orbit of the muon,
the negative particle going

00:33:29.470 --> 00:33:32.960
around the proton,
it is much smaller.

00:33:35.880 --> 00:33:41.790
Therefore, the Lamb
shift also, but also

00:33:41.790 --> 00:33:44.830
the correction due to the
finite size of the proton,

00:33:44.830 --> 00:33:46.865
is much, much
larger because there

00:33:46.865 --> 00:33:49.410
is much more overlay
of the muonic wave

00:33:49.410 --> 00:33:54.790
function with a proton
than for an electron.

00:33:54.790 --> 00:33:56.850
So there was a huge
improvement in the precision

00:33:56.850 --> 00:33:58.810
of the measurement
of the proton size,

00:33:58.810 --> 00:34:01.180
and this has really
led to what's

00:34:01.180 --> 00:34:03.750
called the proton radius puzzle.

00:34:03.750 --> 00:34:08.244
It's not sure if that is at the
same level of the Lamb shift,

00:34:08.244 --> 00:34:10.714
which gave rise to
fundamental new physics.

00:34:10.714 --> 00:34:13.750
Maybe this is the discovery
of the new Lamb shift in 2010,

00:34:13.750 --> 00:34:18.070
and it changes our understanding
of fundamental physics,

00:34:18.070 --> 00:34:20.488
but maybe it's something else.

00:34:20.488 --> 00:34:24.080
The answer is not [INAUDIBLE].

00:34:24.080 --> 00:34:25.620
At least this is 2010.

00:34:25.620 --> 00:34:28.280
A few years of
checking the theory

00:34:28.280 --> 00:34:32.175
and checking the experiment has
not removed the discrepancy.

00:34:32.175 --> 00:34:34.495
Rather to the contrary.

00:34:34.495 --> 00:34:38.541
It has hardened that there
is some discrepancy which

00:34:38.541 --> 00:34:42.219
needs to be resolved.

00:34:42.219 --> 00:34:44.612
So this was just a
little shot of excursion,

00:34:44.612 --> 00:34:47.920
a little bit of summary of
spectroscopy of hydrogen

00:34:47.920 --> 00:34:52.190
over 80 years, from
precursors to the Lamb shift

00:34:52.190 --> 00:34:56.440
to the proton radius puzzle.

00:34:56.440 --> 00:34:58.600
AUDIENCE: So I
know the same group

00:34:58.600 --> 00:35:04.390
was using the same technique to
measure deuterium, maybe helium

00:35:04.390 --> 00:35:07.015
PROFESSOR: I think they want to
do it but they haven't done it.

00:35:07.015 --> 00:35:09.490
That's what they plan to do.

