means that we add one
more vector to the mix.

00:36:26.296 --> 00:36:29.390
In fine structure, we have
orbital angular momentum

00:36:29.390 --> 00:36:32.390
and spin angular
momentum, and we

00:36:32.390 --> 00:36:35.437
discussed how spin orbit
coupling eventually

00:36:35.437 --> 00:36:40.742
couples L and S to J and so
on, but now, we extend the game

00:36:40.742 --> 00:36:46.850
by one more vector, B, an
external magnetic field.

00:36:46.850 --> 00:36:49.750
It really becomes a
player in the game

00:36:49.750 --> 00:36:53.665
because you know that if you
have spin orbit coupling,

00:36:53.665 --> 00:36:58.770
we use the vector model that
L and S couple and precess

00:36:58.770 --> 00:37:04.850
around the axis of J, the
total angular momentum.

00:37:04.850 --> 00:37:08.386
So the game we play when we
couple angular momentum is

00:37:08.386 --> 00:37:10.506
that angular
momentum couple, they

00:37:10.506 --> 00:37:13.210
precess around an axis
that involves some quantum

00:37:13.210 --> 00:37:15.100
numbers and so on.

00:37:15.100 --> 00:37:19.460
But now, you can add a
new quantization axis

00:37:19.460 --> 00:37:22.690
with a magnetic field,
and then angular momenta

00:37:22.690 --> 00:37:26.340
will precess around
the magnetic field.

00:37:26.340 --> 00:37:28.310
And there may be
actually a conflict,

00:37:28.310 --> 00:37:31.157
that for strong magnetic
field, the precession is

00:37:31.157 --> 00:37:33.652
different than in
weak magnetic fields,

00:37:33.652 --> 00:37:36.150
and this is what we
want to discuss now.

00:37:36.150 --> 00:37:47.050
So it is the game
of L, S, and B.

00:37:47.050 --> 00:37:52.090
So what we are adding
with magnetic fields

00:37:52.090 --> 00:37:55.880
is we are adding one term
to the Hamiltonian, which

00:37:55.880 --> 00:38:05.360
is the Zeeman term, where we
have an external magnetic field

00:38:05.360 --> 00:38:08.142
and we couple with
a magnetic moment.

00:38:11.550 --> 00:38:14.970
The one thing which
makes it interesting

00:38:14.970 --> 00:38:18.850
when we discuss fine
structure is the following,

00:38:18.850 --> 00:38:23.560
that we have actually two
components to the angular

00:38:23.560 --> 00:38:26.942
momentum of the atom,
which is the spin

00:38:26.942 --> 00:38:29.720
and the orbital
angular momentum,

00:38:29.720 --> 00:38:33.215
and the two have
different g factors.

00:38:36.000 --> 00:38:38.706
So it's not that
the magnetic moment

00:38:38.706 --> 00:38:41.171
is just proportional to
the angular momentum.

00:38:41.171 --> 00:38:43.841
If the angular momentum
comes from spin,

00:38:43.841 --> 00:38:47.160
it has a different weight than
when the angular momentum comes

00:38:47.160 --> 00:38:49.860
from orbital angular
momentum, and this

00:38:49.860 --> 00:38:52.850
is what we want
to now understand.

00:38:56.490 --> 00:39:00.260
We want to determine what
is the magnetic moment

00:39:00.260 --> 00:39:03.843
of the atom when the
angular momentum has

00:39:03.843 --> 00:39:06.150
two different sources?

00:39:06.150 --> 00:39:09.640
What we will find is we will
find that there is a lambda g

00:39:09.640 --> 00:39:12.520
factor which is sometimes
2, which is sometimes 1,

00:39:12.520 --> 00:39:15.350
or which is sometimes
somewhere in between,

00:39:15.350 --> 00:39:18.550
depending how S
and L are arranged

00:39:18.550 --> 00:39:19.994
with respect to each other.

00:39:26.130 --> 00:39:30.264
So our Hamiltonian is the
Hamiltonian for the atom.

00:39:30.264 --> 00:39:32.685
We know that we
have fine structure,

00:39:32.685 --> 00:39:39.580
we discussed that,
which couples L and S.

00:39:39.580 --> 00:40:14.050
And now have a magnetic
moment due to the spin

00:40:14.050 --> 00:40:17.540
and due to the orbital
angular momentum,

00:40:17.540 --> 00:40:22.363
and then couples to the
external magnetic field.

00:40:22.363 --> 00:40:26.686
In other words, if we had
no fine structure coupling,

00:40:26.686 --> 00:40:30.200
if S and L would not
be coupled, the answer

00:40:30.200 --> 00:40:31.970
would be very simple.

00:40:31.970 --> 00:40:34.970
S just couples to
the magnetic field,

00:40:34.970 --> 00:40:37.462
gives the same [INAUDIBLE],
the g factor of 2,

00:40:37.462 --> 00:40:42.362
and L couples to the magnetic
field with a g factor of 1.

00:40:42.362 --> 00:40:45.870
But now the two are coupled
with respect to each other,

00:40:45.870 --> 00:40:51.205
and if you have L-S coupling,
the projection of S and L

00:40:51.205 --> 00:40:54.680
on the z-axis is not a good
quantum number anymore.

00:40:54.680 --> 00:40:58.620
So therefore, we have
two different terms

00:40:58.620 --> 00:41:01.670
which are diagonal in
two different bases,

00:41:01.670 --> 00:41:05.380
and that's what we
want to discuss.

00:41:05.380 --> 00:41:11.870
So the g factor of orbital
angular momentum is 1.

00:41:11.870 --> 00:41:19.000
The g factor of the
spin is 2, or if you

00:41:19.000 --> 00:41:24.100
want to include the leading
correction here from QED,

00:41:24.100 --> 00:41:26.980
it's the fine structure
constant over 2 pi.

00:41:37.910 --> 00:41:44.120
We did discuss that
the fine structure can

00:41:44.120 --> 00:41:49.650
be related as the Zeeman
energy of the spin

00:41:49.650 --> 00:41:52.180
in a magnetic field
which is created

00:41:52.180 --> 00:41:55.650
by the electron
due to its motion.

00:41:55.650 --> 00:41:57.620
Or, if you take the
frame of the electron,

00:41:57.620 --> 00:41:59.935
the electron sees
the proton orbiting

00:41:59.935 --> 00:42:02.300
around that creates
a magnetic field,

00:42:02.300 --> 00:42:05.980
and this magnetic field
couples to the state.

00:42:05.980 --> 00:42:09.760
So therefore, we can
associate fine structure

00:42:09.760 --> 00:42:13.272
with an internal magnetic
field inside the atom.

00:42:22.620 --> 00:42:25.190
And this internal magnetic
field is rather large.

00:42:25.190 --> 00:42:29.270
It's on the order of 1 Tesla.

00:42:29.270 --> 00:42:35.170
So therefore, for our discussion
of the lambda g factor and fine

00:42:35.170 --> 00:42:36.880
structure in applied
magnetic fields,

00:42:36.880 --> 00:42:45.250
we will assume that we are
in the weak field limit

00:42:45.250 --> 00:42:48.950
where the fine structure
term, the first term,

00:42:48.950 --> 00:42:54.170
is much larger than
the Zeeman term.

00:42:54.170 --> 00:42:55.995
Of course, if you use
very strong magnets,

00:42:55.995 --> 00:42:58.520
you can go to the
high field case,

00:42:58.520 --> 00:43:01.990
but I will discuss explicitly
the transition from weak field

00:43:01.990 --> 00:43:04.810
to high field for
hyperfine structure,

00:43:04.810 --> 00:43:07.573
and the phenomenon
for fine structure

00:43:07.573 --> 00:43:08.862
is completely analogous.

00:43:08.862 --> 00:43:11.760
It just happens at
much higher fields.

00:43:11.760 --> 00:43:15.268
So anyway, I will discuss the
high field case and transition

00:43:15.268 --> 00:43:18.928
with the high field case with
a much more elegant example

00:43:18.928 --> 00:43:22.100
of hyperfine structure
that you can immediately

00:43:22.100 --> 00:43:24.052
apply to fine
structure if you like.

00:43:32.896 --> 00:43:41.210
If I want to solve the problem,
calculate the lambda g factor,

00:43:41.210 --> 00:43:51.080
I could directly calculate
just one matrix element

00:43:51.080 --> 00:43:52.888
and it would be done.

00:43:55.600 --> 00:43:59.240
So all I want to know
is what is the Zeeman

00:43:59.240 --> 00:44:02.830
energy because Zeeman energy
divided by the magnetic field

00:44:02.830 --> 00:44:04.270
is the magnetic moment.

00:44:07.210 --> 00:44:11.960
And since I assume that I'm
in the weak field limit,

00:44:11.960 --> 00:44:15.665
I can simply use the
quantum numbers S, L, and S

00:44:15.665 --> 00:44:22.552
and L coupled to J, and the
magnetic quantum number is nJ.

00:44:29.890 --> 00:44:41.560
So by simply calculating this
expectation value, I'm done

00:44:41.560 --> 00:44:43.935
and I've solved the problem.

00:44:56.190 --> 00:45:00.080
However, I want to do the
derivation using the vector

00:45:00.080 --> 00:45:02.865
model because it provides
some additional insight.

00:45:07.980 --> 00:45:19.730
So in the vector model, we
have L and S coupled to J

00:45:19.730 --> 00:45:21.510
to the total angular momentum.

00:45:25.950 --> 00:45:32.355
And in the vector model, we
assume that L and S rapidly

00:45:32.355 --> 00:45:41.590
precess around J. And therefore,
the only thing which matters

00:45:41.590 --> 00:45:45.528
are the projections.

00:45:45.528 --> 00:45:51.090
Only the projections of L and
S on the J-axis are important.

00:45:53.905 --> 00:45:56.280
So you can say if you have an
rapid precession of L and S

00:45:56.280 --> 00:45:59.220
around J, the transverse
components rapidly average

00:45:59.220 --> 00:46:00.190
out and [INAUDIBLE].

00:46:05.040 --> 00:46:09.075
So therefore, our
Zeeman Hamiltonian

00:46:09.075 --> 00:46:12.750
has to be rewritten
in the following way.

00:46:12.750 --> 00:46:15.290
The Zeeman Hamiltonian
was the magnetic moment

00:46:15.290 --> 00:46:18.930
times the external magnetic
field with a minus sign.

00:46:28.860 --> 00:46:39.420
But what matters is the
projection on the J direction,

00:46:39.420 --> 00:46:44.490
so we do the
projection in this way.

00:46:44.490 --> 00:46:46.640
And also, in the
end, what matters

00:46:46.640 --> 00:46:50.230
is, since the magnetic
moments are aligned with J,

00:46:50.230 --> 00:46:59.880
it is now the scalar product
of the magnetic field with J.

00:46:59.880 --> 00:47:05.950
So in the vector model, we
calculate the Zeeman energies

00:47:05.950 --> 00:47:11.060
in that way, but just to
mention that if you don't

00:47:11.060 --> 00:47:14.450
like the vector model and the
assumption of rapid precession,

00:47:14.450 --> 00:47:16.140
just take this matrix element.

00:47:16.140 --> 00:47:18.190
It's exactly the same.

00:47:18.190 --> 00:47:21.740
In other words, I give
you the intuitive picture

00:47:21.740 --> 00:47:23.440
what is inside those
matrix elements.

00:47:26.480 --> 00:47:29.070
So let's evaluate that.

00:47:36.110 --> 00:47:37.800
Let me factor out
the Bohr magneton.

00:47:42.533 --> 00:47:48.990
We have J squared, taking
one of each bracket.

00:47:48.990 --> 00:47:55.890
And now assuming that the
g factor of the spin is 2,

00:47:55.890 --> 00:48:01.370
the magnetic moment is the
Bohr magneton times L--

00:48:01.370 --> 00:48:09.370
the g factor of L is 1-- plus
S, but the g factor of S is 2.

00:48:09.370 --> 00:48:11.972
So this is now the
magnetic moment accounting

00:48:11.972 --> 00:48:18.140
for the two different g factors
we projected on the J-axis.

00:48:18.140 --> 00:48:23.080
And the second racket,
B dot J becomes

00:48:23.080 --> 00:48:24.710
the value of the magnetic field.

00:48:24.710 --> 00:48:28.160
We assume the magnetic field
points in the z direction,

00:48:28.160 --> 00:48:31.465
so therefore, it is the z
component of the total angular

00:48:31.465 --> 00:48:31.965
momentum.

00:48:40.414 --> 00:48:44.900
Let me collect the simple terms.

00:48:44.900 --> 00:48:54.250
Now L plus 2S,
because L plus S is J,

00:48:54.250 --> 00:49:01.130
can be written as J plus S.

00:49:01.130 --> 00:49:09.630
So now we have the product
of J with J, which gives us

00:49:09.630 --> 00:49:21.140
J squared, and then we need
the product of S and J.

00:49:21.140 --> 00:49:27.310
And as usual, we can get
an expression for that

00:49:27.310 --> 00:49:31.210
by using the summation
of angular momenta.

00:49:31.210 --> 00:49:35.190
If we square it on
the right hand side,

00:49:35.190 --> 00:49:40.510
we have the scalar
product of J and S,

00:49:40.510 --> 00:49:43.005
but we have now the
scalar product of J and S

00:49:43.005 --> 00:49:45.122
expressed by L
squared J squared.

00:49:51.940 --> 00:49:59.416
J squared plus S squared minus
L squared divided by J squared.

00:50:08.820 --> 00:50:18.085
Now, we're just one line
away from the final result.

00:50:24.520 --> 00:50:29.100
Jz is a good quantum number.

00:50:29.100 --> 00:50:32.346
It's MJ, the projection
of the total angular

00:50:32.346 --> 00:50:33.834
momentum on the z-axis.

00:50:40.835 --> 00:50:45.970
The bracket here is
now the famous result

00:50:45.970 --> 00:50:47.360
for the lambda g factor.

00:50:52.800 --> 00:50:56.440
So we have J squared over J
squared, which gives us 1.

00:51:02.730 --> 00:51:08.390
And then I simply put
in the quantum numbers

00:51:08.390 --> 00:51:10.980
for J squared, S
squared, L squared, which

00:51:10.980 --> 00:51:16.020
is J times J plus 1
plus S times S plus 1

00:51:16.020 --> 00:51:23.050
minus L times L plus 1, and
we divide by 2 times J plus 1.

00:51:28.980 --> 00:51:33.930
So therefore, the Zeeman
structure in a magnetic field

00:51:33.930 --> 00:51:37.298
is the Bohr magneton
times the magnetic field

00:51:37.298 --> 00:51:40.100
times the angular momentum
in the J direction,

00:51:40.100 --> 00:51:41.984
but then we multiply
with the g factor.

00:51:48.510 --> 00:51:50.285
These are now limiting cases.

00:51:53.240 --> 00:52:06.452
If we do not have spin,
then the only ingredients,

00:52:06.452 --> 00:52:08.400
the only [INAUDIBLE]
angular momentum

00:52:08.400 --> 00:52:12.110
is orbital angular momentum
and we have a g factor of 1.

00:52:12.110 --> 00:52:15.706
So the lambda g factor
simply becomes gL.

00:52:15.706 --> 00:52:19.190
In the case we don't
have angular momentum,

00:52:19.190 --> 00:52:23.940
you can just evaluate this
expression for L equals 0.

00:52:23.940 --> 00:52:29.780
You find indeed that
the g factor is 2.

00:52:34.235 --> 00:52:37.474
But it can have
different values.

00:52:37.474 --> 00:52:39.904
It depends on the
atomic structure.

00:52:48.550 --> 00:52:50.730
That's all I want to
say about fine structure

00:52:50.730 --> 00:52:51.827
in a magnetic field.

00:52:54.960 --> 00:52:57.080
The next step is now
hyperfine structure.

00:53:14.760 --> 00:53:17.904
We are adding one more
vector to the game.

00:53:17.904 --> 00:53:25.380
So we add angular
momentum of the nucleus,

00:53:25.380 --> 00:53:29.300
so now the game being
played is not only L and S.

00:53:29.300 --> 00:53:36.000
We have I and B. It's a
game of the four vectors

00:53:36.000 --> 00:53:38.794
and eventually how they
precess around each other,

00:53:38.794 --> 00:53:43.715
and that gives rise to the
structure of hyperfine levels

00:53:43.715 --> 00:53:45.432
in an external magnetic field.

00:53:49.150 --> 00:53:54.700
We assume that L and
S have coupled to J,

00:53:54.700 --> 00:53:57.375
so we have actually
a coupling of J, I,

00:53:57.375 --> 00:54:00.953
but now we have an external
quantization axis in Zeeman.

00:54:00.953 --> 00:54:05.770
It has to be due to the
external magnetic field.

00:54:05.770 --> 00:54:07.800
And of course, in
hyperfine structure,

00:54:07.800 --> 00:54:13.710
we discussed that I and J are
no longer conserved angular

00:54:13.710 --> 00:54:17.231
momenta because they couple to
a total angular momentum, which

00:54:17.231 --> 00:54:20.880
is F.

00:54:20.880 --> 00:54:30.100
So our Hamiltonian
is the Hamiltonian

00:54:30.100 --> 00:54:34.780
without any kind of
hyperfine and fine structure

00:54:34.780 --> 00:54:38.350
when we have the hyperfine
coupling, which couples I

00:54:38.350 --> 00:54:44.190
and J with the product
I dot J. And then we

00:54:44.190 --> 00:54:49.050
have an external magnetic
field, which couples

00:54:49.050 --> 00:54:56.646
to the magnetic moment
of the electron.

00:54:56.646 --> 00:55:01.760
This may be a smaller term, but
you can easily carry with us.

00:55:01.760 --> 00:55:05.760
There's also a coupling with the
magnetic moment of the nucleus.

00:55:16.560 --> 00:55:19.480
So in this case, because
the hyperfine structure

00:55:19.480 --> 00:55:21.990
is smaller than
the fine structure,

00:55:21.990 --> 00:55:25.240
I want to discuss both the
weak field and the strong field

00:55:25.240 --> 00:55:25.800
case.

00:55:25.800 --> 00:55:27.966
Because magnetic fields of
a few hundred [INAUDIBLE]

00:55:27.966 --> 00:55:32.020
may actually take into
the high field momentum.

00:55:32.020 --> 00:55:38.324
I want to discuss both the low
field and the high field limit.

00:55:38.324 --> 00:55:43.865
The low field limit implies
that the Zeeman energies

00:55:43.865 --> 00:55:47.124
are much smaller than
the hyperfine splittings.

00:55:53.377 --> 00:56:05.410
And then the way we describe the
system is that J and I couple.

00:56:05.410 --> 00:56:10.650
So J, which is responsible
for the magnetic moment,

00:56:10.650 --> 00:56:16.290
precesses around F, the
total angular momentum,

00:56:16.290 --> 00:56:18.325
but then the total
angular momentum

00:56:18.325 --> 00:56:21.070
precesses around
the magnetic field.

00:56:21.070 --> 00:56:24.830
In other words, you assume that
the coupling between J and I

00:56:24.830 --> 00:56:27.296
is so strong and
they couple to F,

00:56:27.296 --> 00:56:29.060
the magnetic field
is not breaking up

00:56:29.060 --> 00:56:34.700
the coupling between J and
I. J and I together form F,

00:56:34.700 --> 00:56:37.560
and this hyperfine state,
this magnetic moment,

00:56:37.560 --> 00:56:41.669
precesses around B.

00:56:41.669 --> 00:56:42.835
This is sort of the picture.

00:56:42.835 --> 00:56:44.220
You have to get used to it.

00:56:44.220 --> 00:56:46.450
J precesses around
F and F precesses

00:56:46.450 --> 00:56:50.030
around the external
magnetic field, B0.

00:56:55.830 --> 00:56:58.960
But again, if you don't
like the precession model,

00:56:58.960 --> 00:57:01.855
just calculate the
quantum mechanical energy

00:57:01.855 --> 00:57:03.770
that will stabilize
the Hamiltonian.

00:57:03.770 --> 00:57:05.718
The answer is identical.

00:57:22.540 --> 00:57:28.866
The Zeeman Hamiltonian
couples to the magnetic field,

00:57:28.866 --> 00:57:34.850
and we have two contributions
to the magnetic moment,

00:57:34.850 --> 00:57:36.978
the electron of the nucleus.

00:57:36.978 --> 00:57:42.510
And in the weak field
limit, we use a treatment

00:57:42.510 --> 00:57:46.984
which is almost completely
analogous to the treatment we

00:57:46.984 --> 00:57:50.442
used when we derived the
[INAUDIBLE] g factor.

00:57:59.334 --> 00:58:02.166
We can treat the
same as Hamiltonian

00:58:02.166 --> 00:58:10.680
perturbation theory, and
it's exactly analogous

00:58:10.680 --> 00:58:15.810
when we added a weak magnetic
field to the fine structure.

00:58:25.050 --> 00:58:33.150
In the vector model, we
have the coupling of J and I

00:58:33.150 --> 00:58:40.170
to F. The relevant
term in the Hamiltonian

00:58:40.170 --> 00:58:46.800
is we have the magnetic
moment of the electron, which

00:58:46.800 --> 00:58:52.040
is proportionate to J
and it couples to B.

00:58:52.040 --> 00:58:56.020
So this relevant term, this
is fully analogous to what

00:58:56.020 --> 00:58:58.350
I did five or 10
minutes ago, has

00:58:58.350 --> 00:59:02.610
to be replaced in the presence
of the nuclear angular

00:59:02.610 --> 00:59:03.550
momentum.

00:59:03.550 --> 00:59:12.093
We have to project everything
on the axis of the total angular

00:59:12.093 --> 00:59:22.960
momentum, F.

00:59:22.960 --> 00:59:32.210
Therefore, the
Zeeman Hamiltonian

00:59:32.210 --> 00:59:40.495
had the contribution
to the magnetic moment

00:59:40.495 --> 00:59:45.790
due to the electron
and due to the nucleus.

00:59:45.790 --> 00:59:49.100
This is proportionate
to J, but now we

00:59:49.100 --> 00:59:56.620
have to project it onto F. And
similarly, the magnetic moment

00:59:56.620 --> 01:00:01.100
of the nucleus is
proportionate to I,

01:00:01.100 --> 01:00:05.140
but what matters is
the projection on F.

01:00:05.140 --> 01:00:10.650
And since I factored
out the Bohr magneton,

01:00:10.650 --> 01:00:12.950
the magnetic moment
of the nucleus

01:00:12.950 --> 01:00:16.610
is proportionate to
the nuclear magneton.

01:00:16.610 --> 01:00:18.200
I have to account for the ratio.

01:00:24.720 --> 01:00:30.470
What matters now is the
projection of F on B0.

01:00:30.470 --> 01:00:37.020
So therefore, collecting
all the terms,

01:00:37.020 --> 01:00:40.670
we have the Bohr
magneton, which is

01:00:40.670 --> 01:00:43.250
setting the scale
of the interaction.

01:00:43.250 --> 01:00:46.770
The last term is
the magnetic field,

01:00:46.770 --> 01:00:49.950
but the projection of F
onto the magnetic field

01:00:49.950 --> 01:00:56.540
gives us the mF quantum
number, and all the rest

01:00:56.540 --> 01:00:59.707
is called the g factor of
the hyperfine structure.

01:01:04.200 --> 01:01:07.256
And the g factor of
the hyperfine structure

01:01:07.256 --> 01:01:19.090
is-- let me just
simplify and neglect

01:01:19.090 --> 01:01:21.590
the small contribution--
it's 1,000 times smaller--

01:01:21.590 --> 01:01:25.610
of the nuclear magnetic
moment, but if you want,

01:01:25.610 --> 01:01:29.265
you can easily include it.

01:01:29.265 --> 01:01:37.522
With this approximation,
the g factor

01:01:37.522 --> 01:01:47.660
of the hyperfine
structure is this.

01:01:47.660 --> 01:01:53.220
It's proportionate to the
lambda g factor we just derived.

01:01:53.220 --> 01:01:55.120
And then using exactly
the same thing,

01:01:55.120 --> 01:01:58.920
you have J dot F. You
can express it now

01:01:58.920 --> 01:02:02.930
by the quantum numbers of F
squared, J squared, I squared.

01:02:14.964 --> 01:02:21.280
You find the final
result, what are

01:02:21.280 --> 01:02:24.060
the g factors of the
hyperfine levels,

01:02:24.060 --> 01:02:25.980
of the hyperfine states.

01:02:30.310 --> 01:02:35.300
So this is the hyperfine
structure of atoms [INAUDIBLE]

01:02:35.300 --> 01:02:35.970
magnetic fields.

01:02:39.775 --> 01:02:42.568
Let's immediately go to
the high field limit.

01:02:46.800 --> 01:02:54.870
The high field limit means that
the electronic Zeeman energy

01:02:54.870 --> 01:02:59.554
is much larger than
the hyperfine coupling.

01:03:05.130 --> 01:03:17.357
And that means always,
when we treat the problem,

01:03:17.357 --> 01:03:20.766
we first take care of
the big contributions

01:03:20.766 --> 01:03:21.740
to the Hamiltonian.

01:03:21.740 --> 01:03:24.175
We try to solve it, if
possible, [INAUDIBLE].

01:03:24.175 --> 01:03:28.419
And then the weaker term
can be any perturbative.

01:03:28.419 --> 01:03:30.710
So now we are in the situation
that the Zeeman coupling

01:03:30.710 --> 01:03:34.246
is the big term and
the hyperfine coupling

01:03:34.246 --> 01:03:35.980
is the weaker term.

01:03:38.550 --> 01:03:47.060
So in other words, what comes
first now is the Zeeman energy,

01:03:47.060 --> 01:03:51.180
so we are not coupling the
electronic angular momentum

01:03:51.180 --> 01:03:55.084
and the nuclear angular momentum
to total angular momentum

01:03:55.084 --> 01:03:57.820
because this coupling is weak.

01:03:57.820 --> 01:04:02.230
We rather say that
the electronic

01:04:02.230 --> 01:04:05.620
and the nuclear angular momentum
align with the magnetic field.

01:04:05.620 --> 01:04:11.450
We quantize along the direction
of the magnetic field,

01:04:11.450 --> 01:04:14.103
and then later we add
the hyperfine coupling

01:04:14.103 --> 01:04:16.070
in a determinative way.

01:04:16.070 --> 01:04:26.380
So B0 now quantizes
J along the direction

01:04:26.380 --> 01:04:31.449
of the magnetic field,
and therefore we use,

01:04:31.449 --> 01:04:35.345
as a good quantum
number, J, the projection

01:04:35.345 --> 01:04:37.780
of J on the external
magnetic field axis.

01:04:43.530 --> 01:04:51.180
So this takes care of J. J and
mJ are good quantum numbers.

01:04:51.180 --> 01:04:52.180
What about I?

01:04:54.790 --> 01:04:58.070
Does the nuclear
angular momentum

01:04:58.070 --> 01:05:00.645
and the nuclear magnetic
moment strongly couple

01:05:00.645 --> 01:05:03.580
to the magnetic field?

01:05:03.580 --> 01:05:07.315
Well, the answer is
yes, but the argument

01:05:07.315 --> 01:05:09.416
is a little bit more subtle.

01:05:09.416 --> 01:05:13.225
The direct coupling
of the magnetic moment

01:05:13.225 --> 01:05:16.232
of the nucleus with
the magnetic field

01:05:16.232 --> 01:05:24.590
may be smaller than the
hyperfine interaction.

01:05:31.310 --> 01:05:37.480
So then you would say, the
nuclear angular momentum

01:05:37.480 --> 01:05:39.190
should not couple to
the magnetic field.

01:05:39.190 --> 01:05:42.510
It should first be coupled
to the hyperfine interaction.

01:05:45.850 --> 01:05:52.310
The hyperfine interaction
is I dot J. However,

01:05:52.310 --> 01:05:56.290
J, which couples strongly
to the magnetic field

01:05:56.290 --> 01:05:58.576
because it couples
to the Bohr magneton,

01:05:58.576 --> 01:06:01.930
has already been coupled
to the magnetic field.

01:06:01.930 --> 01:06:13.470
So therefore, the hyperfine
interaction, which is I dot J,

01:06:13.470 --> 01:06:17.620
is now modified
because J couples

01:06:17.620 --> 01:06:19.805
to the magnetic
field, which means

01:06:19.805 --> 01:06:23.900
we have to project it onto
the magnetic field axis.

01:06:23.900 --> 01:06:28.379
So therefore, the
nucleus now experiences

01:06:28.379 --> 01:06:30.920
an electronic magnetic moment
or electronic angular momentum,

01:06:30.920 --> 01:06:35.420
which has already been
coupled to the z-axis.

01:06:35.420 --> 01:06:37.610
And therefore, the
hyperfine interaction

01:06:37.610 --> 01:06:43.602
is also coupling the nuclear
angular momentum to the z-axis.

01:06:47.570 --> 01:06:53.150
So therefore, the
result is that it is now

01:06:53.150 --> 01:06:54.945
this indirect coupling.

01:06:54.945 --> 01:06:57.975
You couple the electron
angular momentum to the z-axis

01:06:57.975 --> 01:06:59.835
and the electron
angular momentum

01:06:59.835 --> 01:07:04.600
couples the nuclear angular
momentum to the z-axis.

01:07:04.600 --> 01:07:11.090
So now this quantizes the
nuclear angular momentum

01:07:11.090 --> 01:07:14.600
along the z-axis,
which means that n

01:07:14.600 --> 01:07:17.225
sub I becomes a
good quantum number.

01:07:19.820 --> 01:07:23.910
Anyway, maybe the result is even
simpler than the explanation.

01:07:23.910 --> 01:07:27.980
Our Zeeman
Hamiltonian now simply

01:07:27.980 --> 01:07:34.170
means that we have an
external magnetic field

01:07:34.170 --> 01:07:41.320
and you the electron couples
to the magnetic field,

01:07:41.320 --> 01:07:45.140
so what matters is
the projection, mJ.

01:07:45.140 --> 01:07:54.950
The same happens for the
nuclear magnetic moment,

01:07:54.950 --> 01:07:58.330
and now we have to add the
hyperfine interaction, which

01:07:58.330 --> 01:08:07.340
was originally I dot J, but
since I and J are projected

01:08:07.340 --> 01:08:14.132
on the z-axis, what is really
left over are only mI and mJ.

01:08:17.260 --> 01:08:19.619
I could have gotten this
expression immediately

01:08:19.619 --> 01:08:24.609
by just telling you, J and
I no longer couple to F.

01:08:24.609 --> 01:08:27.440
This is destroyed by a
strong magnetic field,

01:08:27.440 --> 01:08:32.126
and the good quantum numbers are
J and I and their projection,

01:08:32.126 --> 01:08:33.779
mJ and mI.

01:08:33.779 --> 01:08:36.450
And then just writing
down the expectation value

01:08:36.450 --> 01:08:38.490
of the Hamiltonian
in these spaces

01:08:38.490 --> 01:08:41.630
would have immediately
given me this result.

01:08:41.630 --> 01:08:46.510
I wanted to give you the more
mechanistic explanation what's

01:08:46.510 --> 01:08:49.932
going on inside the atom and
what leads to this result.

01:08:57.700 --> 01:09:05.979
I have discussed for you the two
limiting cases, the weak field

01:09:05.979 --> 01:09:11.080
and the strong field case,
but you can solve it also

01:09:11.080 --> 01:09:12.670
for intermediate fields.

01:09:12.670 --> 01:09:23.148
You simply have to do
an exact diagonalization

01:09:23.148 --> 01:09:29.176
of the Hamiltonian,
which involves

01:09:29.176 --> 01:09:30.134
the hyperfine coupling.

01:09:32.760 --> 01:09:36.580
And the hyperfine
coupling, if you want,

01:09:36.580 --> 01:09:41.986
can be diagonalized
as eigenfunctions

01:09:41.986 --> 01:09:48.580
where the quantums numbers
are J, I coupled to F,

01:09:48.580 --> 01:09:57.070
and the projection of F, the
magnetic quantum number is mF.

01:09:57.070 --> 01:10:06.700
But now we have the Zeeman
Hamiltonian, where everything

01:10:06.700 --> 01:10:11.115
is projected on the z-axis,
so we have mJ and mI.

01:10:15.870 --> 01:10:25.250
And the Zeeman term
can be diagonalized

01:10:25.250 --> 01:10:33.156
in a different basis, which is
the basis of J, I, mJ, and mI.

01:10:39.370 --> 01:10:45.950
So I've shown you the weak
field limit, where we simply

01:10:45.950 --> 01:10:48.700
assume those quantum
numbers and calculate

01:10:48.700 --> 01:10:51.850
this term determinatively, and
I've shown you the high field

01:10:51.850 --> 01:10:53.850
limit, where we used
those quantum numbers

01:10:53.850 --> 01:10:57.040
and calculated this
field determinatively.

01:10:57.040 --> 01:11:01.860
But in general, you
just have to write down

01:11:01.860 --> 01:11:04.950
the matrix element of this
Hamiltonian in whatever basis

01:11:04.950 --> 01:11:05.620
you choose.

01:11:05.620 --> 01:11:08.420
You can use the
weak field basis.

01:11:08.420 --> 01:11:09.610
This term is diagonal.

01:11:09.610 --> 01:11:10.540
This is off diagonal.

01:11:10.540 --> 01:11:12.100
Or you can use the
strong field basis

01:11:12.100 --> 01:11:15.849
where this is the diagonal
and this is off diagonal

01:11:15.849 --> 01:11:17.900
and simply diagonalize
your Hamiltonian.

01:11:17.900 --> 01:11:21.070
Find the wave function,
find the I energies.

01:11:21.070 --> 01:11:26.960
And since, for cases
where S equals 1/2,

01:11:26.960 --> 01:11:30.295
it's only a two by two matrix
which has to be diagonalized,

01:11:30.295 --> 01:11:32.654
you can do it
analytically, and this

01:11:32.654 --> 01:11:34.320
leads to the famous
[INAUDIBLE] formula.

01:11:42.060 --> 01:11:59.720
So the solution is
analytic for J equals 1/2,

01:11:59.720 --> 01:12:02.262
and it's a beautiful
example which

01:12:02.262 --> 01:12:04.742
you should solve in your
homework assignment.

01:12:09.210 --> 01:12:10.830
Let me just sketch the solution.

01:12:21.390 --> 01:12:26.350
When you go from the weak field
to the strong field limit,

01:12:26.350 --> 01:12:31.750
the z component of the total
angular momentum in one case

01:12:31.750 --> 01:12:33.516
is mF.

01:12:33.516 --> 01:12:38.560
In the other case,
it is mI plus mJ.

01:12:38.560 --> 01:12:42.850
So when you go from
one limit to the next,

01:12:42.850 --> 01:12:47.682
you connect only states
where mI plus mJ equals mF.

01:12:54.760 --> 01:13:05.160
So the structure of
the general solution

01:13:05.160 --> 01:13:22.360
can be explained by repulsion
and anti-crossings of states

01:13:22.360 --> 01:13:29.796
with the same
[INAUDIBLE] number.

01:13:39.160 --> 01:13:44.180
So let me show you the weak
field, the strong field limit,

01:13:44.180 --> 01:13:46.011
and do a graphic interpolation.

01:13:50.566 --> 01:13:59.410
What I've chosen as an example
is the case of a 2 duplet S 1/2

01:13:59.410 --> 01:14:06.900
ground state and a nuclear
angular momentum of 3/2.

01:14:14.300 --> 01:14:17.340
Examples for that is
sodium and rubidium 87.

01:14:34.780 --> 01:14:35.895
This is magnetic field.

01:14:38.510 --> 01:14:44.053
At weak magnetic field
or zero magnetic field,

01:14:44.053 --> 01:14:50.160
the spin 1/2 couples
to the nucleus in 3/2,

01:14:50.160 --> 01:14:58.035
and that gives to
hyperfine states F

01:14:58.035 --> 01:15:04.965
equals 1 and F equals 2.

01:15:09.940 --> 01:15:15.200
The splitting is given by
the hyperfine constant, a,

01:15:15.200 --> 01:15:23.700
and the hyperfine interaction
is A times H times I times S.

01:15:23.700 --> 01:15:27.010
The structure is such that the
center of mass of the energy

01:15:27.010 --> 01:15:31.700
levels is preserved,
so therefore, one state

01:15:31.700 --> 01:15:33.490
is moved up by 3/4 a.

01:15:33.490 --> 01:15:36.800
The other state is
moved down by 5/4.

01:15:39.720 --> 01:15:41.950
And since F equals 1
has three components,

01:15:41.950 --> 01:15:44.930
F equals 2 has five
components, the center of mass

01:15:44.930 --> 01:15:46.230
is preserved.

01:15:46.230 --> 01:15:51.696
We have calculated the g
factor for those states,

01:15:51.696 --> 01:15:55.150
and the g factor
tells us what is

01:15:55.150 --> 01:15:57.900
the structure in
weak magnetic fields.

01:16:01.730 --> 01:16:07.130
So this is the weak
magnetic field solution.

01:16:07.130 --> 01:16:10.020
At high magnetic
field, you know what

01:16:10.020 --> 01:16:12.180
you have in high magnetic field.

01:16:12.180 --> 01:16:16.060
You have a single electron
which can spin up and spin down.

01:16:16.060 --> 01:16:20.610
So if you have an electron
which is spin up and spin down,

01:16:20.610 --> 01:16:24.560
it pretty much is linear
Zeeman shift for spin down

01:16:24.560 --> 01:16:26.760
and linear Zeeman
shift for spin up.

01:16:34.740 --> 01:16:36.760
This is sort of what we expect.

01:16:36.760 --> 01:16:50.780
So what will happen is
that the energy levels

01:16:50.780 --> 01:16:54.335
will evolve like this.

01:17:02.070 --> 01:17:04.900
So in other words,
we have eight levels.

01:17:04.900 --> 01:17:07.966
We have the structure
at weak magnetic fields.

01:17:07.966 --> 01:17:10.130
At high magnetic
fields, of course,

01:17:10.130 --> 01:17:13.745
we also have eight levels, but
they pretty much group into

01:17:13.745 --> 01:17:17.450
spin up of the electron,
spin down of the electron.

01:17:17.450 --> 01:17:20.400
And then there is a
smaller hyperfine structure

01:17:20.400 --> 01:17:23.470
on top of it because
now the nuclear spin

01:17:23.470 --> 01:17:25.100
can have various orientations.

01:17:25.100 --> 01:17:28.980
And I equals 3/2 state
has four orientations,

01:17:28.980 --> 01:17:31.785
so therefore, electron spin
up and electron spin down

01:17:31.785 --> 01:17:34.830
will obtain four sub-levels.

01:17:34.830 --> 01:17:38.430
And if you ask how
did I connected,

01:17:38.430 --> 01:17:46.950
I've connected the quantum
numbers as such what is here,

01:17:46.950 --> 01:17:50.030
the states are
labeled by mI and mS,

01:17:50.030 --> 01:17:52.995
and here, they're
labeled by mF, but mF

01:17:52.995 --> 01:17:57.095
equals mI plus mS. This
is how you correlate

01:17:57.095 --> 01:17:59.972
the states in the
high field case

01:17:59.972 --> 01:18:02.442
to the states in
the low field case.

01:18:10.660 --> 01:18:20.160
I'm running out of time, but
here, we have mJ equals 1/2.

01:18:20.160 --> 01:18:22.860
Here we have the
electron spin minus 1/2.

01:18:40.420 --> 01:18:45.250
These four levels are now
four different quantum numbers

01:18:45.250 --> 01:18:49.460
for the nuclear
angular momentum, which

01:18:49.460 --> 01:18:57.990
are minus 3/2, minus 1/2,
plus 1/2, and plus 3/2.

01:19:03.970 --> 01:19:06.610
And this is what I meant
by avoided crossing.

01:19:10.942 --> 01:19:12.650
At some point, I think,
draw it yourself,

01:19:12.650 --> 01:19:16.760
put the quantum numbers
on it, and you'll

01:19:16.760 --> 01:19:18.000
learn a lot by doing it.

01:19:18.000 --> 01:19:20.895
What you realize also when
you solve the Hamiltonian

01:19:20.895 --> 01:19:26.480
that this structure can be
explained the following way.

01:19:26.480 --> 01:19:31.346
You will always find you
have some states which

01:19:31.346 --> 01:19:35.450
are stretched, where there
is only one state which

01:19:35.450 --> 01:19:39.980
has the maximum angular
momentum inside all

01:19:39.980 --> 01:19:41.890
the stretched states.

01:19:41.890 --> 01:19:44.080
And then the other
states, you always

01:19:44.080 --> 01:19:50.260
need to find two states
which have the same total mF,

01:19:50.260 --> 01:19:53.630
and those two states
avoid each other.

01:19:53.630 --> 01:19:56.860
You can say, just pointing on
two states, those two states,

01:19:56.860 --> 01:19:59.920
let's just assume
they have the same mF.

01:19:59.920 --> 01:20:01.955
They undergo an
avoided crossing,

01:20:01.955 --> 01:20:04.220
and that's exactly
what you get out

01:20:04.220 --> 01:20:06.730
of the diagonalization
of the two by two matrix.

01:20:06.730 --> 01:20:09.240
So this whole diagram
can be understood

01:20:09.240 --> 01:20:13.090
by you have stretched states
which form a one by one matrix.

01:20:13.090 --> 01:20:16.260
There is no recoupling
taking place.

01:20:16.260 --> 01:20:23.300
And then you have three pairs
of states which form two

01:20:23.300 --> 01:20:27.920
by two matrix, and in each pair,
if you would now focus on it,

01:20:27.920 --> 01:20:31.418
you really see the avoided
crossing typical for a two

01:20:31.418 --> 01:20:32.666
by two matrix.

